                            <comment id="13829541" author="morayani" created="Fri, 22 Nov 2013 01:12:11 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;We are currently working on this.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="13853392" author="morayani" created="Thu, 19 Dec 2013 22:24:49 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;Patch attachment&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="13853399" author="morayani" created="Thu, 19 Dec 2013 22:33:58 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;Code was modified to support hash algorithms besides MD5. A 64-byte fixed array to include support for SHA-512 which uses 512-bit digests.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="13853501" author="morayani" created="Fri, 20 Dec 2013 00:18:52 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;Need corporate approval for the submission.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="13853508" author="cutting" created="Fri, 20 Dec 2013 00:27:43 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;I&apos;m not sure why 16-byte hashes aren&apos;t good enough in this case.  The hashes are of the protocols.  They do not provide security.  They serve to uniquely identify the protocol text required to encode and decode requests.  128 bits should be large enough that collisions are extremely unlikely, which is all that&apos;s required in this application.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Switching to another 128-bit hashing algorithm could be done compatibly, but switching to a different hash size would not be compatible.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
